'''Monroeville Vineyard & Winery''' is a [[winery]] in the [[Monroeville, New Jersey|Monroeville]] section of [[Upper Pittsgrove Township, New Jersey|Upper Pittsgrove Township]] in [[Salem County, New Jersey|Salem County]], [[New Jersey]].<ref name="AC Press">Procida, Lee. [http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/news/top_three/n-j-s-wineries-in-waiting-hope-the-state-will/article_f5e87434-a456-11e0-a043-001cc4c002e0.html "N.J.'s wineries-in-waiting hope the state will rewrite its rules so they can sell"] in ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'' (1 July 2011). Retrieved 7 May 2013.</ref><ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=KgwXCT8eiY8C&pg=PP1&lpg=PP1&dq=sal+westrich+wine&source=bl&ots=Gr5RelIRQ2&sig=s3Et3o2WGiY_jYxSqLd1_2vNGWc&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e6AiUb3aDuTJ0QGj14GADQ&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAw Westrich, Sal. ''New Jersey Wine: A Remarkable History.'' (Charleston, SC: The History Press, 2012). ISBN 9781609491833.]</ref> The vineyard was first planted in 2010, and opened to the public in 2012.<ref name="Monroeville homepage"/><ref>Painter, Nancy Brannigan. [http://onlinedigeditions.com/publication/?i=125897&p=48 "2012 Wine Guide"] in ''[[Edible Communities|Edible Jersey]]'' (Fall 2012). Retrieved 7 May 2013.</ref> Monroeville has 4 acres of grapes under cultivation, and produces wine from New Jersey and Chilean grapes.<ref name="Monroeville homepage"/><ref>Pellegrini, Nicole. [http://www.southjerseyfoodie.com/2012/08/21/monroeville-vineyard-winery-in-monroeville-new-jersey/ "Monroeville Vineyard & Winery in Monroeville, New Jersey"] on South Jersey Foodie (blog) (21 August 2012). Retrieved 7 May 2013.</ref>

==Wines==
Monroeville Vineyard is in the [[Outer Coastal Plain AVA]], and produces wine from [[Cabernet Franc]], [[Cabernet Sauvignon]], [[Chardonnay]], [[Concord (grape)|Concord]], [[Gr<U+00FC>ner Veltliner]], [[Merlot]], [[Muscat (grape)|Muscat]], [[Muscat of Alexandria]], [[Pinot gris]], and [[Syrah]] grapes.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books/about/Garden_State_Wineries_Guide.html?id=3hyfSgAACAAJ Jackson, Bart. ''Garden State Wineries Guide.'' (South San Francisco, CA: Wine Appreciation Guild, 2011). ISBN 9781934259573.] Geographic description of Outer Coastal Plain AVA includes Monroeville Vineyard & Winery.</ref><ref name="Monroeville tasting">Monroeville Vineyard & Winery. [http://monroevillewinery.net/6422.html "Monroeville Vineyard & Winery: Available in Our Tasting Room"] (commercial website). Retrieved 7 May 2013.</ref> Monroeville also makes [[fruit wine]]s from [[apple]]s, [[blueberry|blueberries]], [[cranberry|cranberries]], [[nectarine]]s, [[peach]]es, [[strawberry|strawberries]].<ref name="Monroeville tasting"/>

==Licensing and associations==
Monroeville has a [[New Jersey wine#Winery licenses and regulation|plenary winery license]] from the [[New Jersey Division of Alcoholic Beverage Control]], which allows it to produce an unrestricted amount of wine, operate up to 15 off-premises sales rooms, and ship up to 12 cases per year to consumers in-state or out-of-state.<ref>New Jersey Division of Alcoholic Beverage Control. "[[:File:New Jersey ABC.pdf|New Jersey ABC list of wineries, breweries, and distilleries]]" (5 February 2013). Retrieved 7 May 2013.</ref><ref>[http://law.onecle.com/new-jersey/33-intoxicating-liquors/1-10.html N.J.S.A. 33:1-10.]</ref> The winery is a member of the [[Garden State Wine Growers Association]], and the Outer Coastal Plain Vineyard Association.<ref>Garden State Wine Growers Association. [http://www.newjerseywines.com/wineries.html "GSWGA Wineries."] Retrieved 7 May 2013.</ref><ref>Outer Coastal Plain Vineyard Association. [http://outercoastalplain.com/main/wineries Outer Coastal Plain Vineyard Association Wineries]. Retrieved 7 May 2013.</ref>

